The paragraphs from DORA that are most closely related to the BAIT article are:

1. Article 9, contd.: (d) implement policies and protocols for strong authentication mechanisms, based on relevant standards and dedicated control system, and protection measures of cryptographic keys whereby data is encrypted based on results of approved data classification and ICT risk assessment processes;
2. Article 30, contd.: (iii) the right to agree on alternative assurance levels if other clients’ rights are affected;
3. Article 16, contd.: 3. The ESAs shall, through the Joint Committee, in consultation with the ENISA, develop common draft regulatory technical standards in order to: (b) specify further the elements in relation to systems, protocols and tools to minimise the impact of ICT risk referred to in paragraph 1, second subparagraph, point (c), with a view to ensuring the securit y of networks, enabling adequate safeguards against intrusions and data misuse and preserving the availability, authenticity, integrity and confidentiality of data;

These paragraphs discuss the importance of implementing strong authentication mechanisms, protecting sensitive data, and ensuring the security of IT systems and networks. They also mention the need for regular review and updating of user access rights concepts to ensure that they are in line with protection requirements and comply with the need-to-know and least-privilege principles.
